Here's how to implement all three pieces:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (on `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the Hardware/Gesture Back (in `AppShell.xaml.cs`)

The custom button above handles taps, but the **system back gesture/button** bypasses it. Guard that with `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because the confirmation is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** replaces the default back-arrow tap, so the Shell won't auto-pop; your command handles navigation manually via `GoToAsync("..")`.
- The `OnNavigating` guard catches the Android hardware back button and iOS swipe-back gesture, which bypass `BackButtonBehavior.Command`.
